	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Legend details:
<br />
<br />Video dated 2011/02/18 (NES/Famicom)
<br />* red = background
<br />* green = sprites
<br />
<br />Video dated 2011/02/25 (PC Engine)
<br />* red = background
<br />* green = sprites
<br />* pink = background colour
<br />
<br />Video dated 2011/03/09 (Megadrive/Genesis)
<br />* red = background A
<br />* cyan = background B
<br />* lavender = window
<br />* green = sprites
<br />* pink = background colour
<br />
<br />Video dated 2011/03/26 (SNES/Super Famicom)
<br />Video dated 2011/04/05 (SNES/Super Famicom)
<br />* red = background 1
<br />* cyan = background 2
<br />* lavender = background 3
<br />* yellow = background 4
<br />* green = sprites
<br />* pink = background colour
<br />* Chart in the bottom right indicates video modes (modes 0-7), since each video mode has different capabilities (e.g. different background counts, on-screen colours, and methodology).
<br />* The video mode used is shown on the left hand side of the video window, drawn via coloured bars.  For example, in part of the Super Mario Kart video, the top 1/4th of the screen is dark gray (using mode 0) while the remaining 3/4ths is white (using mode 7).
<br />
<br />Two videos I found amazing (well a lot of them are to me, but still):
<br />
<br />* Lemmings (SNES/SFC): the lemmings aren't sprites, but actually background tiles.  This explains why the lemmings don't flicker when there's a ton of them on a single scanline.
<br />* Gradius 3 and Parodius (SNES/SFC): how Konami did the ship's single-pixel laser effect.
<br />
<br />And of course, all the Yoshi's Story stuff is amazing, but that's also because it uses the FX chip.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
